Category Labels

3.1 Creating spark DataFrame using articles

sentenceData = spark.createDataFrame(data,["label","sentence"])

 

3.2 Data Cleansing by removing stop words

tokenizer = Tokenizer(inputCol="sentence", outputCol="words")
wordsData = tokenizer.transform(sentenceData)

remover = StopWordsRemover(inputCol="words", outputCol="filtered")
filteredWordsData = remover.transform(wordsData)

Fig: Data tokenization and stop words removal

 

3.3 Feature Extraction using Hashing TF and IDF

hashingTF = HashingTF(inputCol="filtered", outputCol="rawFeatures", numFeatures=i)
featurizedData = hashingTF.transform(filteredWordsData)
idf = IDF(inputCol="rawFeatures", outputCol="features")
idfModel = idf.fit(featurizedData)
rescaledData = idfModel.transform(featurizedData)

Fig: Feature Matrix

 

3.4 Data partitioning into training and testing set

(trainingData, testData) = rescaledData.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2])

Conclusion:

No Free Lunch Theorem

It states that no model is indeed the best model for classification. Any model which is fined tuned can perform classification with desired accuracy. In other words, a fined tuned Random Forest Classifier provides more accuracy than an untuned Naive Bayes. Our findings support this theorem.
